<div style="top: 173px; left: 48px; position: absolute; width: 900px; height: auto; background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% transparent;" id="obj-8" class="box clickable ui-draggable ui-resizable ui-resizable-autohide"><span><h1>
  Meldbox is an in-browser web page and app designer for web prototyping and HTML mock ups using advanced CSS3.
</h1>
<br>
<p>
  It utilizes the web browser's natural ability to create visual elements using the newest CSS3 implementations.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Saves time by not having to design or work off of a web layout in Photoshop, Illustrator or Fireworks.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Since CSS is used for designing, the web layout and elements are already mostly coded!
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Easily incorporate front-end frameworks such as Twitter Bootstrap, jQuery mobile UI or a custom framework (coming very soon).
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Design a form as it would appear in a browser without trying to recreate it in a design program like Photoshop, Illustrator or Fireworks (no offense to these programs).
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Simply add a box and make it into a visual web element to create a web page or app design using CSS.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Since it's already in a browser it doubles as an online HTML and CSS previewer (much better than Dreamweaver).
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Built with jQuery, Underscorejs, Backbonejs, FontAwesome, Codemirror, a little bit of PHP and a ton of Javascript.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Programming skills are not required however advanced HTML and CSS developers will be able to pick it up very easily.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It was built by a web developer for web development in an attempt to free the web developer of relying on design software.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It is open source and free.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  PHP is required but can be easily altered to work in any parser.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  The browser designer can be easily customized.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  How-to videos are coming soon!
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It is a browser based online designer so it works on Windows, Linux or Mac.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  The idea came from realizing that web designers were drawing web elements that a browser, using CSS, can already do.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  The functions and features are loosly taken from Fireworks and Firebug.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It is 
  <strong>NOT</strong>
  a web page creator.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It is 
  <strong>NOT</strong>
  for anyone to just willy-nilly make a "web page."
  <br>
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It is a tool to aid a web developer with designing web pages and apps in a browser thus skipping the need to design in a graphics program and then having to code it afterwards.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Meldbox is brand new, just released in June of 2013.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  As of right now there is no documentation, sorry.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Basic instructions and hotkeys are provided in the application
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Works in Firefox/Iceweasel, probably in Chrome, maybe in Safari, not in IE (nor will it ever be, IE sucks!).
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Currently, Meldbox does not have bitmap or vector drawing ability so logos and background images would still be designed in a seperate program.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It's also beta.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Some things will probably be broken
</p>
<br>
<p>
  It's currently in a first release so a lot of features and functionality are missing.
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Got it?
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Good :)
</p>
<br>
<p>
  Here is a penguin
  <br>
  <i class="icon icon-linux" style="font-size: 24px;">
  </i>
